A large number of medicinal plants possess diverse natural compounds, contributing to drug development by providing novel candidate therapeutic agents against various diseases. Natural compounds are small molecules synthesized by living organisms, including primary and secondary metabolites (
 Hanson, 2003). Accumulating evidence has shown that the ingestion of bioactive natural compounds, such as phytochemicals, antioxidants, vitamins, and minerals, through a diet rich in herbs, fruits, vegetables, and spices may promote health via negative immunoregulatory and anti-inflammatory activities (
 Chu et al., 2002; 
 Mursu et al., 2013; 
 Kruk, 2014). Moreover, many natural compounds have been proven to play an important role as modulators of cell signaling and homeostasis, which enforces the need to identify the medicinal potentials of bioactive natural compounds (
 Brindha, 2016; 
 Dias et al., 2016; 
 Pellavio et al., 2017).
